r seat with a padded backrest and large rear storage trunk behind them. The motorcycle’s chrome engine covers, footboards, windshield, and wide saddlebag area are clearly visible. At the upper left, white text reads “Gold Wing 1800.” A few moments later, bold white text appears along the bottom: “‘Motorcycle of the Year’,” with smaller attribution text beneath it to Motorcyclist and Rider magazines. The bike continues steadily past a forested mountain backdrop.\n\nThe commercial returns to a single black Gold Wing on a narrow rural road bordered by golden grass. From above and ahead, the rider approaches along the winding pavement, the motorcycle centered in the lane. The rider leans the bike gently into the curve, and the front headlights and amber side lights are visible. Tall grasses and fence posts line the roadside, giving the setting a quiet countryside feel.\n\nFrom behind, a black touring motorcycle leans through another broad mountain curve. Its red rear lights and large rear trunk are visible as it arcs along the double yellow lines. The rider’s dark helmet and jacket form a compact silhouette above the bike’s wide rear storage cases. Blue-gray mountain ridges and scattered evergreens fill the distance.\n\nAn orange Gold Wing rides through a desert canyon road. Red and tan rock walls rise close beside the pavement, with a natural arch-like opening visible in the rock face behind the motorcycle. The rider wears a black helmet and dark riding clothes, seated upright behind the tall clear windshield. The orange fairing, matching saddlebags, rear trunk, chrome engine area, and bright headlight cluster stand out against the warm rock.\n\nA large gold wing emblem and the word “GOLDWING” appear over a curving mountain road, with “Test Ride” in bold white text beneath. Fine-print legal text fills the lower portion of the screen, including a visible note that the test ride program is good through 4-1-2002 and that dealers may deny participation at their discretion.